metadata.name: Nowhere Stamps #8
metadata.description:
Is it possible to find geographic coordinates or names of the places where the artistic experiment leads us? Does the journey called research have an end point?

We are trying to track it via postage stamps for envelopes coming from there.

Thanks for the aesthetic inspiration to Sigmar Polke, who lived and studied at the Düsseldorf Arts Academy, not far from our current place of living.
His works were called a European Pop art, because of translating everyday life into enigmatic narratives.
Experimenting with materials and chemicals, mixing together traditional pigments with varnishes, toxins and resins to produce spontaneous chemical reactions, he was making art created by chance. He combined analog alchemy with tinting and altering methods on a computer.

In our case, alchemy is the images, produced by the neural networks, the results of which cannot be predicted. One can only guess, try to ask them the right question.

Chemistry and pigments are p5.js tools that also sometimes spontaneously produce unpredictable results.

The process of creating ‘Nowhere Stamps’ became a great journey and adventure in itself.

Work is made in collaboration with artist, musician and poet Yulikolay.

metadata.name: Garden Of Symmetry #349
metadata.description:
Sometimes, things look better when seen from the distance. Not from far away, but from a length that allows one to see what’s possibly underneath. Or, you may not see anything. Instead, you can just enjoy things falling into place.

Get a pack of shattered glass, snow, or ice*, uncovering a pattern. Or an axis of dancing geometries. Enter the Garden of Symmetry.

The graphic is a plottable SVG file in A3 format, ready to be drawn using a pen plotter. In the full screen view, click somewhere on the artwork to download a copy.

I recommend to optimize the SVG before plotting, i.e. using vpype. I also recommend to draw the graphic using 0.7mm pen.

metadata.name: Ethereal Microcosm #86
metadata.description:
An exploration of algorithmic organisms in a contained environment.

This piece is about the simulation of microscopic patterns using a high number of even tinier agents all following the same rules. Different species evolve and interact together, resulting in stabilizing patterns out of their parametric configurations. A form of artificial life.

This work is based on the paper "Characteristics of pattern formation and evolution in approximations of physarum transport networks", written by Jeff Jones and popularized in the artistic field by Sage Jenson. Some features were added to increase the visual and behavioral complexity of the system. Agents are divided into different species, with their own set of rules and interacting with their own substrate. Substrates also interact with each other and agents will mutate in contact of some of them.

metadata.name: Mooncakes: Happy Mid Autumn Festival 2022 #558
metadata.description:
To celebrate the Moon Festival with Mooncakes, we have created a quest to introduce everyone to fxhash. As part of that quest on mooncakes.fun, users are encouraged to mint this generative token.

This is a layered image composition using the Mooncakes site images on a 1920x1080 canvas. The image elements are randomly assigned position, scale, tint, and blur according to a ruleset which generates a Mid Autumn Festival scene made up of: Moon, Clouds, Stars, Lanterns, and Lotuses.

Special filters, shapes and colors are included as rare features, as well as a couple of surprises.

metadata.name: Emotional Shell #465
metadata.description:
Manual Dutch Auction (DA): 72 · 54 · 40 · 30 · 24 · 20 every 8 minutes.
Auction will stop changing price when non-reserves are fully minted, and then drop one price tier.

---------

The feeling of being human – with all of its intricate hopes, struggles, and fleeting emotions – seems so unique that we assume artificial intelligence could never replicate our experience. And while we devise systems for solving unfathomably complex problems, generating algorithmic creativity, and unlocking regenerative biological possibilities, we simultaneously cling to the power and originality of emotional feeling – believing it to be the irreplaceable source of what makes us human.

If the body is our shell for emotion and soul, can an artificial humanoid be another vessel for these thoughts and feelings – for human essence itself? If our ‘soul’ is the last stand between us and the machines, what happens when the soul becomes transferable? That we may see answers to these questions looks more real every year, and is perhaps a little frightening. 

Emotional Shell uses introspective portraits of future selves to question what it means to be human, when the people around us are no longer human.

---------
